      {
        "id": 3898488,
        "name": "Ilkka |_ |_| mme",
        "username": "IlkkaL",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/ilkkal/{size}/2504_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-09-20T15:12:08.312Z",
        "cooked": "<p>For my palate 2016 was the last classic Beaujolais vintage with delightfully low ABV levels so I am constantly keeping my eyes open for bottles from this year. Getting harder and harder but recently came across this one and a Chiroubles from Lafarge-Vial. In all honesty this is possibly just a tad more natty than I would prefer but still I can help but adore it for its classic proportions, freshness and joie de vivre. I truly wish that we can still get these 12.5% wonders in the future, if not then in each and every vintage. An epic midweek wine, nothing less.</p>\n<p>[list][*]<span class=\"bbcode-b\">2016 Famille Dutraive Ch\u00e9nas En Papolet</span><span class=\"bbcode-i\"> - France, Burgundy, Beaujolais, Ch\u00e9nas (20.9.2022)</span><br>\nA wonderfully fragrant nose of raspberries and red cherries. Has a tangy, sauvage feel to it with a rather obvious but not over the top VA character - splendid! On the palate there is good mouthfeel and presence and some grip as well. What there is not much of though is weight as it is energetic, refreshing and tons of fun. It is altogether tangy and savory, just full of crunchy red fruit. Clearly natty without taking away from the enjoyment factor as long as it is chilled. Closer to room temp the flavor profile starts to remind a bit of tomato soup.[/list]<br>\n<span class=\"bbcode-i\">Posted from <a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com\" data-bbcode=\"true\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">CellarTracker</a></span></p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 8,
