        "created_at": "2022-09-21T05:43:03.064Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"melvinyeo\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"288993\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/ecb155/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> melvinyeo:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Thanks for this Ilkka, I do like the 2016 Bojos that I have tried as well, and having seen similar alcohol levels on 2021s have bit on a few. Hopefully they mark a return to more classic wines rather than the souped up versions in recent years.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>As usual you seem to be 100% correct! The early releases I see one of my fave retailers listing are all between 12.5% and 13%, even Lapierre whose ABV levels have been out of control lately. I reckon I have to buy a handful and see whether this vintage marks a return to a more classic style indeed. Thanks for the heads-up!</p>",
